%I A278299 #52 Mar 18 2026 21:04:42
%S A278299 2,4,6,9,12,15,19,24,30,34
%N A278299 a(n) is the tile count of the smallest polyomino with an n-coloring such that every color is adjacent to every other distinct color at least once.
%C A278299 Only edge-to-edge adjacencies are considered.
%C A278299 The sequence is bounded above by A053439(n-1).
%C A278299 a(n) is bounded below by n * ceiling((n - 1)/4). This bound is achieved for n=2, n=6, and n=10.
%C A278299 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 07 2026: (Start)
%C A278299 Upper bounds: a(12) <= 40, a(13) <= 47, a(14) <= 56, a(15) <= 61, a(16) <= 69, a(17) <= 78, found by simulated annealing with Numba JIT compilation. The same solver matches the known values for a(2) through a(11). For n >= 12, proving optimality by exhaustive search has not been achieved; the values are constructive upper bounds. All solutions verified for connectivity, color count, and completeness of the binomial(n,2) adjacency pairs.
%C A278299 Conjecture: for each r in {2,3,4,5}, the subsequence a(r), a(r+4), a(r+8), ... has constant second difference equal to 8. This predicts a(18) = 90, a(19) = 96, a(20) = 106, a(21) = 117. Based on a(2)-a(17). (End)
%H A278299 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A278299">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%e A278299 Example: for n = 4, the following diagram gives a minimal polyomino of a(4) = 6 tiles:
%e A278299       +---+---+
%e A278299       | 1 | 4 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 4 | 3 | 2 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+
%e A278299           | 1 |
%e A278299           +---+
%e A278299 Example: for n = 10, the following diagram gives a minimal polyomino of a(10) = 30 tiles. Note that redundant adjacencies, e.g., between 2 and 7, can exist in minimal diagrams.
%e A278299               +---+---+
%e A278299               | 8 | 6 |
%e A278299           +---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299           | 3 | 2 | 5 | 9 | 4 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 2 | 7 | 5 | 1 | 4 | 2 | 10| 9 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 6 | 9 | 8 | 3 | 6 | 7 | 8 | 1 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 10| 3 | 4 | 7 | 1 | 10| 5 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299 From _Ryan Lee_, May 14 2019: (Start)
%e A278299 Example for n = 11:
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 9 | 11| 2 | 5 | 8 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 1 | 5 | 10| 9 | 2 | 1 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 4 | 6 | 11| 8 | 7 | 3 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 3 | 9 | 7 | 10| 6 | 2 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 11| 4 | 5 | 3 | 8 | 4 |
%e A278299   +---+---+---+---+---+---+
%e A278299   | 1 | 10|   | 6 | 1 | 7 |
%e A278299   +---+---+   +---+---+---+
%e A278299 (End)
